[One hopes that the affected girl will recover from her EEE virus infection. About 1/3 of individuals who develop EEE encephalitis subsequently suffer neurologic sequelae. One hopes that the girl is an exception. This year (2019) has been an unusually active one for EEE virus transmission to humans, horses, and some wild animals in the eastern and Midwestern USA.

The 1st reported EEE case in the 2019 season was a horse in Georgia (see Eastern equine encephalitis - North America: USA (GA) horse 20190320.6377189). There have been sporadic human and equine EEE cases in the southeastern USA states this year. The 2019 transmission season has ended in the northern and other states with the occurrence of freezing temperatures terminating mosquito activity. It is not possible to predict if next year (2020) will have as many human and horse cases, but as the summer progresses people should avoid mosquito bites and horse owners should vaccinate their animals. - Mod.TY

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Georgia, United States: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6821543,5614]
